If you mean “what belongs in the same conceptual family as electrons and photons?” there are several ways to answer depending on the level you’re looking at.

Fundamental particles (Standard Model)

These are the basic building blocks we currently know of:

* Electron — carries electric charge; matter particle (a lepton).
* Photon — carrier of the electromagnetic force (a gauge boson).
* Quarks — make up protons and neutrons.
* Neutrinos — extremely light, weakly interacting particles.
* Gluons — carry the strong nuclear force.
* W⁺, W⁻, Z bosons — carry the weak nuclear force.
* Higgs boson — associated with the Higgs field and particle masses.

If you’re thinking in terms of engineering “media”

Then electrons and photons are two examples of physical carriers of information or energy. Others include:

* Phonons (quantized vibrations in solids)
    * Carry heat and sound through materials.
    * Important in quantum technologies and thermal engineering.
* Magnons
    * Collective spin waves in magnetic materials.
    * Studied for low-power computing (spintronics).
* Excitons
    * Bound electron-hole pairs in semiconductors.
    * Important in LEDs, solar cells, and quantum materials.
* Plasmons
    * Collective oscillations of electrons.
    * Can confine light below the diffraction limit (plasmonics).
* Polaritons
    * Hybrids of light (photons) and matter excitations.
    * Blend properties of both.

If you’re abstracting the pattern

You can think of these as different substrates or carriers:

Carrier	Best at
Electrons	Computation, electrical power
Photons	Communication, sensing
Phonons	Mechanical vibration, heat transport
Magnons	Spin information
Ions	Electrochemistry, batteries, neurons
Molecules	Chemical information, biology
DNA/RNA	Long-term biological information storage

An interesting pattern emerges: many emerging technologies are about choosing the right carrier for the right job. Instead of making electrons do everything, engineers increasingly use specialized carriers—photons for communication, electrons for logic, ions for energy storage, spins for memory, and so on.

That “carrier selection” viewpoint is becoming a useful design principle in fields from AI hardware to quantum engineering.